        <methods>
            <methodStep>
                <description>
                    <para>Mainly ‘Field observation’, but other sources as well.</para>
                </description>
            </methodStep>
            <qualityControl>
                <description>
                    <para>HBRG records on the Atlas are all, at the time of entry, &apos;Considered correct&apos; as used in the primary database Recorder 6, and as understood in simple English.  All records are subject to demanding quality checks, all due diligence being applied.  Each is literally &apos;Considered correct&apos; in the context of current taxonomy, local flora and fauna, and with knowledge of the skills of the determiner.  We do not use &apos;Correct&apos; as a) taxonomy changes; b) composition of our flora and fauna changes; and c) all determiners are human and therefore - however experienced - can make errors.  There are many examples where these factors have applied to make &apos;Correct&apos; inappropriate.

This is NOT the definition of ‘Considered correct’ as used on the NBN Atlas and by BRC where it is stated ‘The partner/verifier has not seen photo/s or specimen/s’.

If errors come to light, the record is flagged on NBN Atlas, listed in
https://www.hbrg.org.uk/Dataset/Errors_HBRG_NBN_Atlas_datasets.xlsx, and corrected at the next update to the Atlas.</para>
                </description>
            </qualityControl>
        </methods>

